# The memory system: map + health

## The short version

Your machine watches everything you and your agents do, writes the good
parts down as pages in the Brain, and a picky curator texts you the best
bits — then records which emoji you react with. The plumbing for that
whole loop moved one real reaction end to end on 2026-07-17. Whether the
grades actually make the curator *better* is unproven — one 👍 is a
smoke test, not a verdict.

Around the healthy core, three things need attention soon: the nightly
condenser has a blind spot that starts mattering around 2026-07-18, the
graph builder would leak sensitive page titles if anyone rebuilds it, and
**71 GB of failed capture uploads** are quietly piling up in a retry
folder. And there's clutter: four old memory systems are dead but still
plugged in — one of them still answers `joelclaw recall` with data from
May as if it were today. The fix list at the bottom is ordered by blast
radius; the top two are one-sitting jobs.


that captures, condenses, stores, curates, delivers, or grades durable
knowledge for you and your agents — mapped in plain words, then graded.
Verdicts are `working` (does its job, receipts prove it), `wobbly` (exists
but degraded or fragile), `gap` (missing, or exists and nothing consumes
it). Every claim here traces to one of four survey assets with full
receipts; links at the bottom. Four pi workers surveyed the live system in
parallel; nothing on this page is from memory.

## The loop in one breath

Everything you and your agents do on flagg becomes raw session capture.
The observer distills that into observation pages in the Brain. Dreams
condense aging pages into rollups. The neat-memory curator reads the
Brain, judges what's worth your attention, and DMs you the best of it on
its own schedule. You react with an emoji, and that grade flows back into
the judge's history for the next beat. The wiki renders the whole Brain at
brain.joelclaw.com. That's the core loop — capture → condense → store →
curate → deliver → grade — and as of today every stage runs, with the
grading loop proven end to end by your own 👍.

## Capture — working

Sessions on flagg stream into `~/.joelclaw/runs-dev/` and the observer
tick (every 30 minutes, LaunchAgent `com.joelclaw.observer-tick`) walks
new activity windows, distills them on Terra subagents, and writes
schema-v1 observation pages to the user Brain
(`dark-wizard/.brain/observations/`). The substrate is genuinely growing:
652 top-level pages plus 85 archived, with fresh pages minutes old at
survey time and pending-publish at 0. All three observer LaunchAgents
(tick, dream, neat-memory) report status 0.

Two caveats. The kind taxonomy is messy — 42 pages missing `kind`, nine
different kind strings — which makes grouping noisier than it should be.
And the dev checkout had drifted ahead of the deployed release during the
review (details under Delivery).

## Condense (dreams) — wobbly

The dream machinery is real and proven: the supervised 2026-07-14 run
condensed 85 aged pages into 26 rollups at 0.81 compression, archived the
originals, and left a receipt page. But the unattended nightly run has
written nothing since — `eligiblePages: 0` every night. The survey settled
why: it's not the cap, it's corpus youth. Under the live rule (plain pages
need 7 days), a scan of all 652 pages found zero eligible anywhere — the
oldest current page is from 2026-07-11. The wave comes when the corpus
ages in.

The real risk is still coded in: the dream reads `files.slice(0, cap)` —
the first 200 pages by sorted filename — *before* checking eligibility,
and the log has said `capped:true` daily since 07-15. Once pages past the
first 200 age in, the dream won't see them until earlier names condense.
That deserves a fix before the ~07-18 eligibility wave.

## Retros — gap

The curator reads `dark-wizard/.brain/resources/retros/` as a first-class
candidate source, but nothing writes there as part of any pipeline. Two
retro files exist, both hand-made. If retros are supposed to be memory,
they're currently a manual side door, not a stage.

## Store + render — working, with edges

The Brain is `.svx` trees governed by one registry
(`dark-wizard/brain-roots.json`). Four roots are registered — `user`
(1,121 pages), `joelclaw` (261), `observer` (23, registered today as part
of this review), `wiki` (67) — and the renderer prerenders each page at
`brain.joelclaw.com/<root>/<slug>/` with privacy exclusions applied
(excluded sections plus `privacy: sensitive` never render). The pipeline
from file to URL is clean, compile failures are page-scoped, and fleet
sync through dark-wizard is healthy.

The edges: flagg has **31** `.brain` trees; 27 are orphans the wiki can't
see. That's not automatically wrong — but there's no gate proving each
orphan is intentionally local versus forgotten. And the `.svx` law's
enforcement is narrow: only joelclaw-wiki runs the checker in lint, and 11
`.md` files sit outside any ratchet, including one unratcheted straggler
in joelclaw's own tree that currently fails its check.

## The graph — wobbly, one sharp edge

The Brain Graph projection (932 nodes / 805 edges) is five days stale — it
predates the observer root and a week of writes — and its rebuild is a
separate manual script that the normal wiki build never runs. The sharp
edge: **`graph-builder.ts` has no privacy boundary.** It ingests every
`.svx` including sensitive pages, and the neighborhood/backlink UI prints
node labels without filtering. The live graph only has zero sensitive
nodes because it's stale. Rebuild it today and hundreds of sensitive
titles leak into page-side rendering. Fix the boundary before anyone
refreshes the graph.

## Curate — working

The neat-memory curator is the newest organ and it's healthy. Candidates
come from observations + retros (7-day lookback, public/private only,
dedupe-forever against sent state). The judge is sol:xhigh behind the
27-line simple prompt (`observer/neat-memory-simple-v1`) — no meta
framing, only `history` and `candidates` substitutions, send bar at
score ≥ 8, silence encouraged. It paces itself: the judge names its own
`nextBeat` (clamped 2h–48h), the shell schedules it via `joelclaw wake`
with receipt-checked envelopes, and the daily 16:15 LaunchAgent is only a
dead-man that revives a dead chain. The chain is provably alive: beats
fired 04:19 → 10:19 → 16:20 today, self-scheduling 6h/6h/12h, next
pending for 04:20 tomorrow.

## Deliver — wobbly, honestly

Your DMs arrive over the legacy notify path today, and that path works.
The rebuilt Chat SDK acting path — the one that caused the 07-16
confirmed-but-invisible incident — is fixed at the source (confirmation
now structurally requires a platform message id plus journal readback) but
sits dark behind `CHAT_SDK_ACTING_ENABLED=0` pending the supervised
re-flip with the visible-delivery canary. Wobbly means exactly that:
delivery has two truths, and the fixed one is source-verified rather than
production-verified.

One live find from this review: the deployed release checkout was running
*old* curator code — still sending DMs `--priority low` without
`--telegram-only`, because the priority-high commit was never promoted.
The promotion happened mid-review (release now at `af7b5437`), so the
16:20 beat's DM rode the old lane; check whether you actually saw the
"milestone-win" DM from 16:20Z. Release promotion is manual and just
proved it can drift silently — it wants a receipt-checked script.

## Grade — plumbing works; learning unproven

Telegram reactions flow: poller (reaction updates enabled) → shadow tap →
`message/inbound.reaction` on the bus → the bridge correlates platform
message to flowId → `message/reaction.received` → the grading consumer
maps 👍 ❤️ 🔥 💯 to `worked` and 👎 💩 to `did-not-work`, then atomically
writes the outcome into the curator's state file. Your real reaction
graded `2026-07-17-248a3715344a` to `outcome: "worked"`, and the judge's
prompt builder includes outcomes in the history it sends to sol:xhigh. So
the pipe is real and the grades reach the judge's eyes. What's NOT shown:
that any of it changes the judge's picks. One reaction is a smoke test;
"the curator learns your taste" stays an open claim until there's enough
graded history to see selection actually shift.

Residual softness: today's state entries lack `flowId`, so grading can
fall back to a two-minute timestamp match. Safe while sends are sparse;
worth tightening as volume grows.

## The periphery — eleven more stores, graded

**Working (4):**

- **Memory pulse** — the wiki's read-only status projection over the core
  loop; live JSON fresh at survey time, sensitive pages filtered.
- **Typesense + pdf-brain** — 662 books, 241,939 active chunks, NAS
  artifacts current; a research corpus, deliberately not operator memory.
- **Voice work recall** — stateless adapter over the session archive; 12
  tests green; fails closed on sensitive content.
- **Voice transcripts** — private/public/guest split enforced at write
  time; public speech never enters the memory pipeline.

**Wobbly (4):**

- **Claude auto-memory** — a live shadow source. It duplicates operator
  truths that belong in the Brain, and it wrote a fresh topic page on
  07-17, *after* your 07-16 Brain-only instruction. Kill it or make it a
  read-only pointer into the Brain.
- **Chorus / rhizomatic claims** — the service runs and session identity
  is fresh, but the semantic layer is June canary residue: zero
  preferences, zero tasks, newest durable claims from 06-18, and 13
  mutations stuck in its outbox. Decide: canary or real substrate.
- **Run capture archive** — the raw episodic substrate is fresh and
  indexed, but **the outbox holds 14,798 failed POSTs totaling 71.38 GB**
  accumulating since 06-08, and at least one live gateway session still
  posts to a 404 route. That's not a retry buffer anymore.
- **MEM/FRIC suites** — the old memory path's acceptance tests are no
  longer 23-red (49 pass / 1 timeout today) but they protect the legacy
  pipeline, not the core loop, and they leak real 401s from live Inngest.

**Gap (3):**

- **`memory_observations`** — the legacy recall index: 28,050 documents,
  **99.26% stale**, newest observation 2026-05-31, and `joelclaw recall`
  still answers from it as if current. A competing memory that stopped
  learning six weeks ago.
- **Legacy `MEMORY.md` promotion path** — reflect/promote/review functions
  still registered against a curated file that doesn't exist on flagg. A
  zombie: code without a substrate.
- **System log** — `~/Vault/system/system-log.jsonl` is absent on flagg;
  `slog` silently reads a stale panda copy (newest row 06-22) while panda
  is being decommissioned. The receipt ledger has split brain.

## What deserves work next

In rough order of blast radius:

1. **Graph privacy boundary** — before anyone rebuilds `graph.json`.
2. **Dream cap fix** — before the corpus ages into eligibility (~07-18).
3. **Drain + repair the 71 GB capture outbox** — find the 404 route,
   replay safely, add a size/age alarm.
4. **One legacy-memory retirement** — `memory_observations`, the MEMORY.md
   zombie, generic voice recall, and MEM/FRIC as a single explicit
   migration, not five separate corpses.
5. **System log home** — move it to flagg or declare panda's archival.
6. **Claude auto-memory + Chorus decisions** — each is one sitting.
7. **Release promotion script** — receipt-checked, so deploy drift can't
   recur.
8. **Retro writer** — make retros a real stage or stop pretending.

## How this page stays honest

This page is a snapshot from the 2026-07-17 review, built by four parallel
survey workers reading the live system — the provenance commit stamp below
tells you how stale it is. When the memory system changes materially
(cutover re-flip, legacy retirement, graph fix), regenerate it from a
fresh survey rather than patching sentences: the effort brief and its four
survey assets are the template. Full receipts live there:

